{"text": "2 2 2 2 :::p\n\n2 2 2 2 :::p\n\n2 2 2 2 :::\n\n::: ::: ::: ::: :::1\n\nCCCCA(45.22)\n\nEnergy levels: Without a scatterer the eigenenergies are:\n\nEn(\b;u=0) =1\n\n2m\u00122\u0019\n\nL\u0002integer\u0000\b\n\nL\u00132\n\n; integer = 0;\u00061;\u00062;::: (45.23)\n\nOn the other hand, in the limit u!1 the system does not \"feel\" the \rux, and the ring becomes a one-dimensional\n\nbox. The eigenenergies in this limit are:\n\nEn(\b;u=1) =1\n\n2m\u0010\u0019\n\nL\u0002integer\u00112\n\n; integer = 1;2;::: (45.24)\n\nAs one increases uthe number of the energy levels does not change, they just move. See\n\ngure below. We would like\n\nto use perturbation theory in order to\n\nnd corrections to the above expressions. We consider how we do perturbation\n\ntheory with respect to the u=0 Hamiltonian. It is also possible to carry out perturbation theory with respect to the\n\nu=1Hamiltonian (for that one should use the formula for the interaction at a junction).\n\n223\n\n9\n\n4\n\n1\n\n016En\n\nu=\u2212 u=0 u=+88\n\nThe corrections to the energy: Let us evaluate the\n\nrst-order correction to the energy of the eigenstates in the\n\nabsence of an external \rux.\n\nEn=0 =E[0]\n\nn=0+u\n\nL(45.25)\n\nEn=2;4;::: =E[0]\n\nn+2u\n\nL\n\nThe correction to the ground state energy, up to the second order is:\n\nEn=0= 0 +u\n\nL+\u0010u\n\nL\u001121X\n\nk=1(p\n\n2)2\n\n0\u00001\n\n2m\u00002\u0019\n\nLk\u00012=u\n\nL\u0012\n\n1\u00001\n\n6umL\u0013\n\n(45.26)\n\nwhere we have used the identity:\n\n1X\n\nk=11\n\nk2=\u00192\n\n6(45.27)\n\nOptional calculation: We will now assume that we did not notice the symmetry of the problem, and we chose to\n\nwork with the\n\nrst basis. Using perturbation theory on the ground state energy is simple in this basis:\n\nEn=0= 0 +u\n\nL+\u0010u\n\nL\u00112\n\n21X\n\nk=1(1)2\n\n0\u00001\n\n2m\u00002\u0019\n\nLk\u00012=u\n\nL\u0012\n\n1\u00001\n\n6umL\u0013\n\n(45.28)\n\nBut using perturbation theory on the rest of the states is di\u000ecult because there are degeneracies. The\n\nrst thing we\n\nmust do is \"degenerate perturbation theory\".", "embedding": [-0.00401746, 0.00086653436, 0.022568261, -0.0065403576, -0.010780927, -0.019790808, -0.025356498, -7.598617e-05, -0.037547525, 0.07292793, 0.05708852, 0.012065186, 0.0146871, -0.024335254, -0.03825312, 0.04668193, 0.015957551, -0.0022120625, -0.074857086, 0.031578667, 0.009965372, -0.021119194, -0.07024216, -0.01605383, -0.04869657, 0.040742308, 0.015944311, 0.01040836, 0.06916185, 0.057037327, 0.039683428, -0.023966964, -0.009907956, -0.029619088, 0.0021018675, 0.001014631, -0.007528534, -0.018059872, 0.038748425, -0.05074479, 0.03872808, -0.047665548, 0.009662996, -0.027026996, -0.026728757, 0.010173011, 0.005242981, 0.004895347, -0.0067172046, -0.06480535, 0.013987885, 0.008727638, 0.013290499, -0.003346165, 0.025705459, 0.0053061703, -0.0038700586, 0.021510419, -0.02633726, -0.01465065, 0.04172035, 0.0147732245, 0.027213195, -0.0070989453, 0.02085487, 0.061089274, -0.0036817782, 0.0492936, -0.009498025, -0.060745284, -0.03209782, -0.03468032, -0.027657636, -0.0116930595, -0.031483877, 0.03828614, -0.0011673941, -0.02286005, -0.0783944, -0.025637435, -0.014588103, -0.01608625, -0.017188586, 0.0071269344, -0.029266216, -0.004026882, -0.007031697, -0.011862865, 0.0039818627, 0.021582838, 0.018416649, 0.054700155, -0.011121856, -0.012404969, 0.019687835, 0.036761876, 0.0055674277, 0.022783501, 0.034008548, 0.009208426, -0.021073774, 0.022953242, 0.011459189, 0.033593457, -0.059824344, 0.0249367, -0.014261899, 0.018214233, 0.03571779, -0.054769453, 0.0017251791, -0.013294262, 0.038735412, 0.056154788, 0.020009223, 0.029613407, 0.018736046, -0.0037682261, -0.011257825, -0.022111408, 0.023472914, -0.0062818136, 0.01424503, 0.015850315, -0.0076319897, 0.004078742, 0.0017226638, 0.005315071, -0.030442066, 0.007637046, -0.0029356827, -0.008355703, -0.0026791603, 0.007520761, -0.020331126, 0.019134829, -0.015314329, 0.018891709, 0.018553296, -0.013765798, 0.030